Fueling Innovation In Medical Devices (And Beyond): Venture Capital In Health Care


D. Clay Ackerly, 
                     
Ana M. Valverde, 
                     
Lawrence W. Diener, 
                     
Kristin L. Dossary and 
                     
Kevin A. Schulman



                           Duke Clinical Research Institute, Duke University School of Medicine, in Durham, North Carolina
                           
                        



Kevin Schulman (kevin.schulman{at}duke.edu)
                     




 Next Section
Abstract
Innovation in health care requires new ideas and the capital to develop and commercialize those ideas into products or services.
                     The necessary capital is often “venture capital,” but the link between public policy and the venture capital industry has
                     not been well examined. In this paper we explore the link between venture capital and innovation in health care, and we present
                     new descriptive data from a survey of health care venture capital fund managers. Respondents generally viewed policy levers
                     (for example, reimbursement and regulations) as important risks to venture capital investments, potentially affecting their
                     ability to raise capital for early-stage investment funds.
                  



The amount of venture capital dollars in health care may be viewed as a proxy for the amount and type of innovation being
                        supported.
                     


Medical advancement through research and development in prescription drugs, devices, and services has had a dramatic impact on health care in
                  the United States. Innovation has shifted surgical procedures from highly to minimally invasive, moved therapies from late-stage
                  treatment to early treatment and prevention, and created treatments for previously incurable diseases.1 The growing burden of disease in the United States and worldwide suggests that the need for innovation will remain high.
               
Innovation in health care requires new ideas and the capital to develop those ideas into marketable products. Increasingly,
                  innovation occurs in small, early-stage companies that rely heavily on venture capital.2 After a product reaches a certain stage of development, these small companies are frequently acquired by larger companies
                  to complete the development, production, and marketing of products.3 This is particularly the case in the pharmaceutical industry, in which larger companies look to start-up companies to supplement
                  their product pipelines.4 It has been estimated that 17.5 percent of sales from the twenty largest pharmaceutical companies in 2002 was derived from
                  in-licensed products and that this proportion would increase to 26.1 percent in 2010.5 Thus, venture capital funds play a critical role in providing early-stage financing to bring technologies past the financial
                  “valley of death,” to the point at which they become attractive to a wider spectrum of investors, including larger pharmaceutical
                  companies and even the public through initial public offerings (IPOs).6
The positive impact of venture capital funding on innovation can be dramatic.7 Venture capital is a large source of financing for developing new ideas into health care products (more than $10 billion
                  in 2007 alone).8 One dollar of venture capital is about three times more effective in producing patentable ideas than a dollar spent on traditional
                  corporate research and development (R&D).9 Because the health sector is unique in the sheer volume and magnitude of risks facing companies (regulatory, reimbursement,
                  liability, and so on), changes in policy-induced risk can be expected to affect both the ability of fund managers to raise
                  capital and the types of health care investments made once the money is raised. However, the research literature has largely
                  not evaluated the link between public policy and venture capital. To our knowledge, no previous studies have explored the
                  perceptions of venture capital fund managers and the ways in which policy changes affect their ability to raise funds for
                  investments in early-stage life sciences companies.
               
Therefore, the purpose of this paper is to describe the health care venture capital industry and its impact on health care
                  innovation; to describe current venture capital flows across the major health sectors of devices, biotechnology, and services;
                  and to explore the perceptions and experiences of venture capital fund managers to identify the risks and drivers of health
                  care venture capital investment.
               

Previous SectionNext Section
Exploring Venture Capital

What is venture capital?
Put simply, venture capital firms are institutional managers of risk capital. Typically, they invest in ideas whose developers
                        cannot access traditional forms of capital (bank or corporate funds) because of their early stage of development, and they
                        are intimately involved in the formation and governance of the start-up companies in which they invest.
                     
Before they make investments, fund managers must raise investment dollars from institutional investors or high-net-worth individuals.
                        First, they establish an investment fund with a specific investment profile. If they raise the targeted funding, they close
                        the fund and begin to invest it according to the criteria they agreed upon with their investors. Investors’ dollars remain
                        in the fund until the investments are liquidated, sometimes more than a decade later. Once a fund has been fully committed
                        (that is, invested in start-up companies), fund managers often raise capital for a sequential fund and repeat the process.
                     
Venture capital investments are illiquid and inherently risky; the companies are privately held, have few tangible assets,
                        and typically require five to eight years to reach the stage where a “liquidity event” or “exit,” such as an IPO or acquisition
                        by another company, will be feasible. According to the National Venture Capital Association, only 14 percent of funded companies
                        ever go public, and another 33 percent are acquired. The rest (53 percent) either publicly announce their failure or quietly
                        disappear.10
In exchange for significant risk, venture capital investors expect significant returns. The latest industry data show an average
                        net internal rate of return of 17.9 percent annually over the past ten years.11 To achieve a result of this size, a subset of investments within a fund must have returns much greater than average to make
                        up for the many expected failures.
                     


Impact of venture capital on innovation and the economy.
Because of the private status of most start-ups and venture capital firms, information on the venture capital industry is
                        difficult to obtain. Proprietary databases track some industry statistics such as deal flow, but finding data on returns from
                        individual investments, let alone calculating the societal benefit from them, is a challenge. However, anecdotal evidence
                        is strong.12 Also, some studies suggest that there is a dramatic impact. For example, one study revealed that whereas the ratio of venture
                        capital investment to overall industrial R&D spending was less than 3 percent, venture capital accounted for 15 percent of
                        industrial innovations as measured through patent filings.13
Venture capital–backed companies start small but do not always stay small. Some of the largest U.S. companies were backed
                        by venture capital, including blue-chip companies such as Home Depot, Starbucks, Google, Microsoft, Medtronic, and Genentech.
                        In 2006, sales of venture capital–backed firms amounted to $2.3 trillion, or 17.6 percent of gross domestic product (GDP).14 In the same year, 9 percent of all private jobs in the United States (more than 10 million in total) were in venture capital–backed
                        companies, and job growth in these firms during 2003–2006 was 3.6 percent, compared with overall private-sector growth of
                        1.7 percent.15 Furthermore, 83 percent of employees in the medical device sector in 2006 worked for venture capital–backed companies.16


Trends in venture capital spending.
Venture capital under management in the United States at the end of 2007 amounted to $257 billion, and investments made in
                        that year reached $30 billion—the fourth annual increase in a row, but still less than a third of the $100 billion reached
                        in 2000, the peak bubble year.17 In 2007 an estimated 741 venture capital firms were operating in the United States, each of which ran an average of two separate
                        funds. About one-third of the firms actively raised money in 2007, leading to almost $40 billion in capital raised.18


Venture capital in health care.
Health care has been a major focus of the venture capital industry in recent years, representing 31 percent of total venture
                        capital investments in 2007.19 For analysis purposes, the health care industry can be split into three general sectors: (1) pharmaceutical and biotechnology
                        products; (2) devices (for example, pacemakers, stents, glucose monitors); and (3) services (for example, home health care,
                        back-office services, and other), with the lion’s share of investment targeting products and devices.
                     
The medical device sector is of particular interest because it has seen dramatic increases in absolute investment and increased
                        market share within health care, reaching 45 percent in 2007, as compared to 35 percent in 2004 (Exhibit 1⇓).20 In 2007 the largest single area of medical device investment was surgical instruments and equipment—$844 million, or 20.4
                        percent of the total $4.1 billion invested in devices. The rest was split between therapeutic devices (including defibrillators),
                        diagnostics, and other items.21 Biotechnology investment, on the other hand, is fragmented; no single product category accounted for more than 12 percent
                        of the total $5.2 billion invested in the product sector. Investments in services are more homogeneous, with almost half of
                        the investments in 2007 ($117 million out of $249 million) being focused on long-term, home, and elder care.22

