Annual Venture Capital Investment, By Health Care Sector, 1998–2007






Previous SectionNext Section
Descriptive Survey Of Venture Capital Fund Managers
Despite venture capital’s importance in financing early-stage companies that are critical to technological innovation in health
                     care, little is known about the impact of public policy on managers’ ability to raise funds. Thus, we created a survey targeting
                     venture capital fund managers to begin to explore these issues.23
The survey was designed to address the following issues: (1) how the firm’s money was invested and how such investments have
                     changed over time; (2) the fund manager’s perceptions of the greatest risks both to the success of the portfolio companies
                     and to the firm’s ability to raise capital; (3) how changes in reimbursement and regulatory risks might affect venture capital
                     fund flows; and (4) how risk-return profiles vary across the health care investment sectors.
                  
Twenty fund managers met the inclusion criteria and completed the survey. Although these numbers are not sufficient to generate
                     statistically significant results, the collective opinions of the respondents provide important insights. The respondents
                     averaged 12.4 years of experience in the venture capital industry (range, 1–30 years), and their funds had invested in more
                     than 1,100 companies, with more than $13.5 billion currently under management, $7.0 billion of which was devoted to health
                     care. The distribution of investments across health care sectors in respondents’ portfolios is consistent with national data,
                     and respondents reported increasing their investments in medical devices, also consistent with the national trend. Given the
                     lack of previous documentation of fund managers’ perceptions and values, the survey results provide a useful starting point
                     for discussion and further evaluation.
                  

Ability to raise capital.
Fund managers were asked to rate the importance to their investors of several factors (Exhibit 2⇓). Their responses were not unexpected. All but one considered the potential return given the risk of the portfolio as a factor
                        that either mattered “very much” or was “all that mattered.” Other important factors in raising health care funds were the
                        experience of the management team in the portfolio company (sixteen of twenty) and the novelty of the technology or service
                        (fourteen of twenty). All other factors (including public health impact) were less important: 70 percent or more of the respondents
                        considered them only moderately important or less.
                     


View this table:
In this window
In a new window



EXHIBIT 2 
Factors That Are Important To Investors When Deciding Whether To Invest In Health Care



Of the three most important factors affecting the ability to raise capital, the risk-return profile is the only factor that
                        can be affected by changes in regulatory and reimbursement policies. Respondents largely agreed on the importance of the relationship
                        between returns and regulatory and reimbursement policies, ranking reimbursement, intellectual property (IP) protection, and
                        the efficiency of the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) review process as the most important risks affecting portfolio companies’
                        returns.
                     


Medical devices versus biotech and drug products.
Data from the venture capital industry showing steady increases in the absolute and relative magnitude of investments in the
                        device sector might reasonably be interpreted as demonstrating the relative attractiveness of this sector, compared to biotechnology
                        or other sectors, as a result of factors such as lower development costs, shorter development times, and reduced regulatory
                        hurdles.24 The results of the survey support this interpretation. Respondents were asked to rate the three sectors by risk-return ratio.
                        Unlike the biotechnology and pharmaceuticals markets—which all respondents viewed as high risk—the device market yielded a
                        variety of opinions, including a quarter of managers who felt that the device market yielded high returns with low risks—an
                        ideal combination, if truly achievable.
                     
Respondents were also asked to rank a series of risks to the success of their portfolio companies. Investors who focused on
                        the biotechnology and pharmaceutical markets ranked the efficiency of the FDA review process as the most important risk to
                        their portfolio companies; they were less concerned with reimbursement. This is to be expected, given the longer development
                        times and higher regulatory hurdles facing biotechnology and pharmaceutical products compared to medical devices and the targeted
                        exit strategy of acquisition for many of these firms.25 Conversely, device-focused firms were more concerned about reimbursement than about the FDA review process. This finding
                        may reflect the relatively rapid FDA processes for devices and, thus, the relative importance of reimbursement to the early
                        stages of the device business model.
                     


IP protection and product liability.
IP protection and product liability are two areas of potential risk to companies, but respondents’ views of their relative
                        importance were divergent. IP protection was the third-ranked risk (after reimbursement and FDA processes). On the other hand,
                        product liability did not elicit much concern, despite recent high-profile challenges to large companies (for example, Merck
                        and Vioxx).26
Concern about IP protection is not surprising, given both the IP output of venture-backed companies and, because of the size
                        of the companies, their reliance on patent protection to maintain barriers to market entry by competitors. Venture capital
                        fund managers may also view this area as important because of recent uncertainty regarding the future of IP protection in
                        the United States.27 Conversely, product liability was not considered an important risk, which may reflect the early-to-mid-stage nature of venture
                        capital investments, with venture funds typically exiting before liability issues can become a concern.
                     


Sensitivity to changes in risk.
The survey suggests that an increase in risk (specifically, regulatory and reimbursement risk) has a major impact on the investment
                        strategies of venture capital funds. Approximately two-thirds of respondents said that increases in risk would lead them to
                        shift investments within or across health care sectors or to reduce health care investments altogether. Although the survey
                        did not attempt to quantify the relationship between variations in risk and changes in investment strategy, these findings
                        are worthy of reflection. Of the $67 billion invested in health care by venture capital firms since 2000, less than 20 percent
                        was invested by firms focused on health care (that is, “pure-play” firms).28 Because most investments are being made by non-pure-play firms, the scope for shifting out of health care investment and
                        into other areas is large. Furthermore, the scope for shifting investments within health care (including from areas of high
                        to low public health impact) remains high. As one respondent wrote, “Regulatory risk is a primary consideration when considering
                        potential investments. Generally, it decreases the chance that an investment will be made in a ‘new area’ and increases the
                        chance an investment will be made in a ‘me-too’ space.” Investors “want big exits,” wrote another respondent. “Lower reimbursement
                        lowers the ultimate exit value of individual portfolio companies. Investors who want to stay in health care will shift investments
                        from life saving products…to consumer-pay cosmetic opportunities. …That trend has already started in anticipation of decreased
                        reimbursement.”
                     
These two comments reveal both a level of concern about reimbursement and regulatory risk and a degree of freedom for managers
                        to shift investments within the health care sector to maximize returns. Unfortunately, these risk-mitigation strategies could
                        result in a lower net public benefit from venture capital–backed technologies.
                     
Looking forward, the picture does not look any brighter for the venture capital industry. When managers were asked how they
                        saw reimbursement risk changing in the future, none thought that it would improve.
                     


Business model for public health.
In examining the link between venture capital, health care policy, and public health benefit, it is helpful to recognize that
                        the supply of venture capital investment can be affected by poor public policy throughout the investment cycle. Once a venture
                        capital firm makes a given investment in a start-up company, funds are typically locked in for a number of years. However,
                        investment decisions for the uncommitted portion of the funds are fluid, and changes in federal policies could have a major
                        effect even in the short term. Moreover, venture capital firms tap the capital markets regularly to raise new funds for investments
                        in sectors that are deemed attractive at that time. Thus, venture capital firms may respond to perceived unfavorable policies
                        either by adjusting their strategies to lower-risk investments within the health care sector (with possibly lower societal
                        benefits) or by leaving the sector altogether in the ensuing round of fund-raising.
                     
The ease with which venture capital firms change strategy and behavior (particularly away from risky areas that might have
                        the greatest potential to improve public health) is not unexpected. Fund managers perceived that their investors consider
                        financial returns to be their primary concern and that the public health benefit of their investments is of little importance.
                        Thus, policymakers should not lose sight of the fact, self-evident to some, that private-sector innovations designed to improve
                        public health require business models that make them financially viable and provide attractive returns on investment.29
One good example of a public policy decision that recognized this important dynamic and implemented a solution that aligned
                        business and public health interests was the Pediatric Exclusivity Provision of the FDA Modernization Act of 1997.30 Given a dearth of clinical trials that examined the safety of drugs in children, Congress granted six months of market-exclusivity
                        extensions to companies that conducted pediatric safety studies for those products. Despite some debate about whether six
                        months of exclusivity was too generous, this policy has increased the number of pediatric trials.31 In 2007, Congress extended the program for another five years.32
Examining the interplay between policy and health care venture capital reveals a need to further explore and monitor the interdependencies
                        among policy, industry, and the public interest. One solution might be to systematically collect data from the venture capital
                        community (whether it be opinion data or investment strategy data, as laid out in fund-raising documents) to understand their
                        perceptions of public policy and its contribution to investment risk, the types of investments new funds will consider, and
                        the success of health care funds in raising new investment dollars. These data can provide valuable insight into early barriers
                        to innovation (much as the FDA’s Critical Path Initiative examined this issue from the perspective of downstream users of
                        the regulatory process).33
In short, the public health returns from venture capital investment are both fluid and sensitive to public policy risk. Thus,
                        policy-makers (and the public they serve) may benefit from a system that monitors the impact of policy on the venture capital
                        industry’s ability to invest in technologies that can improve health and health care.
                     



Previous SectionNext Section
Concluding Comments
Innovative ideas in health care can come from many places, and their creators often turn to venture capital to turn those
                     ideas into biotechnology or pharmaceutical products, medical devices, or health care services. This is particularly the case
                     as more large drug and device companies look to smaller start-up companies to help fill their product pipelines.34 Thus, the amount of venture capital dollars in health care may be viewed as a partial proxy for the amount and type of innovation
                     being supported. Protecting a vibrant venture capital sector is an important means of stimulating innovative health care delivery.
                     Federal policies can have a direct impact on the risks and returns of venture capital investments. They can also affect both
                     the ability of the venture capital industry to raise capital for investments in health care and how that money is invested
                     once raised. Therefore, given venture capital’s important contributions to innovation in health care, policymakers should
                     make a concerted effort to better understand the link between their policy levers and the venture capital industry.
                  






